00:00:26.420 --> 00:00:31.950
JOSH: OK, so let's turn
the page to storyboarding,

00:00:31.950 --> 00:00:35.710
which, for us, no matter
what sort of video

00:00:35.710 --> 00:00:38.330
you're doing-- live
action, animation,

00:00:38.330 --> 00:00:45.425
or some sort of combination--
is vital to the process.

00:00:49.350 --> 00:00:52.260
And here's why.

00:00:52.260 --> 00:00:57.300
It allows you, basically,
a lot of freedom

00:00:57.300 --> 00:01:03.140
to not have to make any really
high stakes creative decisions

00:01:03.140 --> 00:01:07.750
and just be creative
at a very early stage.

00:01:07.750 --> 00:01:09.850
You don't have to commit
to any sort of production

00:01:09.850 --> 00:01:11.600
at that point.

00:01:11.600 --> 00:01:13.460
That's why we do it.

00:01:13.460 --> 00:01:15.550
And it's why we
share with clients

00:01:15.550 --> 00:01:19.040
before we commit to
doing any animation,

00:01:19.040 --> 00:01:22.262
because it's very time
consuming for us to animate.

00:01:22.262 --> 00:01:23.720
And we want the
client to know what

00:01:23.720 --> 00:01:26.470
we're doing before we commit
to doing any of that really

00:01:26.470 --> 00:01:27.485
labor-intensive work.

00:01:30.410 --> 00:01:33.805
It serves as a blueprint
for timing and visual flow.

00:01:33.805 --> 00:01:38.630
So you can get a sense of
the pacing of the video,

00:01:38.630 --> 00:01:41.120
whether or not, as
Elizabeth was saying,

00:01:41.120 --> 00:01:44.300
things are going to get
stale at a certain point.

00:01:44.300 --> 00:01:46.550
It can help you make those
sorts of creative decisions

00:01:46.550 --> 00:01:49.330
without having to commit
a lot of resources.

00:01:52.220 --> 00:01:55.940
The storyboard can
reveal where you're

00:01:55.940 --> 00:01:58.950
going to need to shoot, what
props you're going to need,

00:01:58.950 --> 00:02:03.710
the types of shots
you're going to employ.

00:02:03.710 --> 00:02:05.370
All that decision
making gets made

00:02:05.370 --> 00:02:08.729
in the storyboarding process.

00:02:08.729 --> 00:02:10.680
And another, really
crucial thing

00:02:10.680 --> 00:02:13.240
is, so often when we're
doing a storyboard,

00:02:13.240 --> 00:02:16.490
we realize that the script
needs to be different.

00:02:16.490 --> 00:02:19.450
You write something-- maybe
you have some visual sense when

00:02:19.450 --> 00:02:20.560
you're writing a script.

00:02:20.560 --> 00:02:23.960
And that's good, because--
and I've done it a lot.

00:02:23.960 --> 00:02:25.690
So a lot of times I
am thinking visually.

00:02:25.690 --> 00:02:28.250
But I'm not always
thinking visually.

00:02:28.250 --> 00:02:32.690
And I'm not-- it's not my
strong suit all the time

00:02:32.690 --> 00:02:33.764
when I'm script writing.

00:02:33.764 --> 00:02:35.930
So a lot of times, we'll
be in a storyboard meeting.

00:02:35.930 --> 00:02:38.730
And we'll say, well, this
line is just sort of dumb.

00:02:38.730 --> 00:02:41.810
Why don't we say this so
that we can show this?

00:02:41.810 --> 00:02:47.500
So that integration of
visual and oral-- the voice--

00:02:47.500 --> 00:02:49.970
is a really crucial
part of storyboarding.

00:02:53.130 --> 00:02:56.350
So that's why we storyboard.

00:02:56.350 --> 00:02:58.550
And let me just
show you an example

00:02:58.550 --> 00:03:00.500
of one of our storyboards.

00:03:00.500 --> 00:03:02.560
There are many different
ways to storyboard.

00:03:02.560 --> 00:03:04.780
But I'll just show
you one example.

00:03:04.780 --> 00:03:06.710
The first is--
well, I'll show you

00:03:06.710 --> 00:03:11.460
the storyboard for this video
we did for NASA, actually.

00:03:11.460 --> 00:03:16.020
And it was produced
by WNET in New York.

00:03:16.020 --> 00:03:18.960
And they asked us to
create a series of videos

00:03:18.960 --> 00:03:20.380
about different physics topics.

00:03:20.380 --> 00:03:23.950
And this one is on
centripetal force.

00:03:23.950 --> 00:03:30.230
So I'll just switch
over to-- let's see,

00:03:30.230 --> 00:03:40.205
episode-- So this
is essentially--

00:03:40.205 --> 00:03:42.340
this is our storyboard method.

00:03:42.340 --> 00:03:45.100
We do an Excel spreadsheet
with three columns--

00:03:45.100 --> 00:03:47.270
shot, narrator, and notes.

00:03:47.270 --> 00:03:51.845
Very simple-- email me, and
I'll send you this storyboard.

00:03:51.845 --> 00:03:56.270
And you can use it in
your own work if you want.

00:03:56.270 --> 00:03:57.870
Imagine you've
got a tennis ball.

00:03:57.870 --> 00:04:01.380
So we start the shot
on the tennis ball.

00:04:01.380 --> 00:04:03.302
We either pull back--
we'll watch the video.

00:04:03.302 --> 00:04:05.010
I can't remember if
the camera pulls back

00:04:05.010 --> 00:04:09.150
or we jump cut or something--
attached to a piece of string.

00:04:09.150 --> 00:04:10.680
And we pull back further.

00:04:10.680 --> 00:04:14.360
And you start swinging it.

00:04:14.360 --> 00:04:16.670
And then-- when did we
have this idea for the dog?

00:04:16.670 --> 00:04:19.000
I mean, probably this came
in the storyboard meeting.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:23.030
Like, OK, we'll have this nice
dog element to the experience.

00:04:25.640 --> 00:04:29.430
In circles-- and so
gradually, the camera's

00:04:29.430 --> 00:04:30.440
getting further back.

00:04:30.440 --> 00:04:31.856
And now we can see
the background.

00:04:34.630 --> 00:04:40.790
"Whoa now, watch
out for your buddy."

00:04:40.790 --> 00:04:42.370
This is not for
adults, by the way.

00:04:42.370 --> 00:04:42.870
I'm sorry.

00:04:42.870 --> 00:04:45.120
I should've mentioned that.

00:04:45.120 --> 00:04:47.850
This is for, like, elementary
and middle schoolers.

00:04:47.850 --> 00:04:51.350
So if you find this a
little facile and dumb,

00:04:51.350 --> 00:04:53.720
just imagine you're
13 years old.

00:04:56.390 --> 00:04:57.580
"Watch out for your buddy."

00:04:57.580 --> 00:05:00.560
So the guy on the
skateboard ducks down.

00:05:00.560 --> 00:05:02.530
And then he goes past and waves.

00:05:05.270 --> 00:05:09.910
Let's take-- so we start
with-- my attitude about this,

00:05:09.910 --> 00:05:12.564
in a lot of cases, is
to start with action.

00:05:12.564 --> 00:05:14.730
Like, start with something
that's really compelling.

00:05:14.730 --> 00:05:17.150
Like, some-- you don't
have to start, right away,

00:05:17.150 --> 00:05:18.030
explaining things.

00:05:18.030 --> 00:05:22.550
Just sort of start with
imagining something or doing

00:05:22.550 --> 00:05:23.070
something.

00:05:23.070 --> 00:05:24.840
There's that old
comment, I think--

00:05:24.840 --> 00:05:28.160
this is Hemingway said this, he
talked about "in medias res."

00:05:28.160 --> 00:05:30.320
Start in the middle of things.

00:05:30.320 --> 00:05:32.990
So don't start with
elaborate explanations.

00:05:32.990 --> 00:05:35.650
Just start in the
middle of the action.

00:05:35.650 --> 00:05:37.650
So something needs
to be happening

00:05:37.650 --> 00:05:40.860
at the beginning of a video.

00:05:40.860 --> 00:05:42.800
So that's why we
chose to start--

00:05:42.800 --> 00:05:44.035
you got this ball spinning.

00:05:44.035 --> 00:05:45.160
There's something going on.

00:05:45.160 --> 00:05:46.700
There's this dog.

00:05:46.700 --> 00:05:48.210
There's the kid
skateboarding by.

00:05:48.210 --> 00:05:50.080
You're starting
with a high level

00:05:50.080 --> 00:05:51.450
of engagement and interest.

00:05:54.280 --> 00:05:57.720
Let's take a closer look
at the fascinating physics

00:05:57.720 --> 00:06:01.590
of this simple action.

00:06:01.590 --> 00:06:05.050
And then we go into the
more detailed analysis

00:06:05.050 --> 00:06:06.180
of what's really going on.

00:06:06.180 --> 00:06:10.310
We talk about f equals
ma-- Newton's second law--

00:06:10.310 --> 00:06:12.107
and how it relates
to objects moving.

00:06:12.107 --> 00:06:14.190
So I'm not going to show
you the whole storyboard.

00:06:14.190 --> 00:06:16.920
But you start to get a sense of
how we put this thing together

00:06:16.920 --> 00:06:23.590
visually in a very methodical
way before we did any work-- I

00:06:23.590 --> 00:06:27.450
mean, this is work-- but
before we did any animation

00:06:27.450 --> 00:06:28.890
or illustration.

00:06:28.890 --> 00:06:31.610
And I think John did all
the artwork for this.

00:06:35.130 --> 00:06:37.410
And it's very basic.

00:06:37.410 --> 00:06:39.080
She's basically a stick figure.

00:06:39.080 --> 00:06:41.460
John makes really
nice stick figures.

00:06:41.460 --> 00:06:42.753
So he has that talent.

00:06:45.780 --> 00:06:48.940
So let me just
show you the video.

00:06:48.940 --> 00:06:51.325
And it came out of that process.

00:06:55.690 --> 00:06:58.400
Hold on a second.

00:06:58.400 --> 00:06:58.920
There we go.

00:07:07.180 --> 00:07:10.760
Whoops, that's
not the right one.

00:07:10.760 --> 00:07:12.880
Here we go.

00:07:12.880 --> 00:07:14.370
This is a minute and 46.

00:07:14.370 --> 00:07:17.440
So our challenge was
to do these topics

00:07:17.440 --> 00:07:21.792
in about a minute and a half,
a minute and 45 seconds.

00:07:21.792 --> 00:07:22.750
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:07:22.750 --> 00:07:24.860
-Imagine you've got a
tennis ball attached

00:07:24.860 --> 00:07:25.980
to a piece of string.

00:07:25.980 --> 00:07:28.160
And you start swinging
it in circles.

00:07:28.160 --> 00:07:28.930
Whoa, now!

00:07:28.930 --> 00:07:30.700
Watch out for your buddy!

00:07:30.700 --> 00:07:33.350
Let's take a closer look
at the fascinating physics

00:07:33.350 --> 00:07:35.040
of this simple action.

00:07:35.040 --> 00:07:37.650
You've probably heard of
Newton's second law of motion

00:07:37.650 --> 00:07:40.490
as it relates to objects
moving in a straight line.

00:07:40.490 --> 00:07:42.600
Turns out, Newton's
second law also

00:07:42.600 --> 00:07:44.870
tells us about the
net force on an object

00:07:44.870 --> 00:07:46.570
as it moves in a circle.

00:07:46.570 --> 00:07:48.320
When an object
moves in a circle,

00:07:48.320 --> 00:07:50.420
its velocity changes direction.

00:07:50.420 --> 00:07:52.430
Since the velocity's
changing, that

00:07:52.430 --> 00:07:54.270
means we have an acceleration.

00:07:54.270 --> 00:07:56.060
And we know from
Newton's second law

00:07:56.060 --> 00:07:59.250
that if we have an acceleration,
we have a net force.

00:07:59.250 --> 00:08:01.080
Now back to our spinning ball.

00:08:01.080 --> 00:08:03.380
For objects undergoing
circular motion,

00:08:03.380 --> 00:08:06.580
the net force on the object is
called the "centripetal force."

00:08:06.580 --> 00:08:09.800
It's a weird sounding word,
but it's Latin for the phrase

00:08:09.800 --> 00:08:11.270
"center-seeking."

00:08:11.270 --> 00:08:14.570
It's named centripetal because
the centripetal force always

00:08:14.570 --> 00:08:16.800
points to the center
of the circle.

00:08:16.800 --> 00:08:18.900
The ball has a
tangential velocity.

00:08:18.900 --> 00:08:20.580
So if you suddenly
cut the string,

00:08:20.580 --> 00:08:23.920
it would fly off in whatever
the tangential direction was

00:08:23.920 --> 00:08:25.960
at the moment you made the cut.

00:08:25.960 --> 00:08:27.650
But assuming you
don't cut the string,

00:08:27.650 --> 00:08:30.900
and you keep swinging the ball,
the ball's tangential velocity

00:08:30.900 --> 00:08:33.010
is constantly
changing directions.

00:08:33.010 --> 00:08:35.210
This means the ball
is accelerating.

00:08:35.210 --> 00:08:37.000
And the reason it's
accelerating is

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:39.020
due to the centripetal force.

00:08:39.020 --> 00:08:41.140
The centripetal force
acting on the ball

00:08:41.140 --> 00:08:43.580
is constantly directing
the ball towards the center

00:08:43.580 --> 00:08:45.340
of the circle, your hand.

00:08:45.340 --> 00:08:47.570
This, combined with
the ball's velocity,

00:08:47.570 --> 00:08:49.810
keeps the ball
swinging in a circle.

00:08:49.810 --> 00:08:52.620
The same centripetal force that
keeps the tennis ball swinging

00:08:52.620 --> 00:08:55.455
in a circle also keeps
roller coasters on the track

00:08:55.455 --> 00:08:57.590
as they go through
a loop-de-loop.

00:08:57.590 --> 00:09:00.410
So the next time you're having
a blast on a roller coaster,

00:09:00.410 --> 00:09:02.707
you can thank the
centripetal force.

00:09:02.707 --> 00:09:03.290
[END PLAYBACK]

00:09:03.290 --> 00:09:11.200
JOSH: OK, so that's a
pretty short little ditty.

00:09:11.200 --> 00:09:14.750
But you can-- I just wanted
to show you how we built it.

00:09:17.440 --> 00:09:22.990
And this next thing is-- I'm not
going to show the whole thing.

00:09:22.990 --> 00:09:24.760
But it's interesting.

00:09:24.760 --> 00:09:27.370
This is a video, a sort
of an insider look at how

00:09:27.370 --> 00:09:30.057
Pixar does their storyboarding.

00:09:30.057 --> 00:09:31.640
And I'll just play
a little bit of it.

00:09:31.640 --> 00:09:33.920
And then perhaps you can
watch the whole thing

00:09:33.920 --> 00:09:34.680
on your own time.

00:09:37.496 --> 00:09:38.340
