a certain chunk done,

00:09:58.060 --> 00:10:00.610
we'll show them
to the directors.

00:10:00.610 --> 00:10:02.247
Or they will show them to us.

00:10:02.247 --> 00:10:04.830
And, I don't know, it's kind of
complicated thing to explain--

00:10:04.830 --> 00:10:06.955
-Well, you know, that was
a really good description

00:10:06.955 --> 00:10:09.214
of about how better
to describe--

00:10:09.214 --> 00:10:10.380
-Something better than that.

00:10:10.380 --> 00:10:10.879
-Yeah.

00:10:10.879 --> 00:10:11.985
-Well, we could show it.

00:10:11.985 --> 00:10:12.860
-Yeah, let's show it.

00:10:12.860 --> 00:10:13.610
-With storyboards.

00:10:13.610 --> 00:10:15.030
-With storyboards.

00:10:15.030 --> 00:10:18.870
OK, this is the
storyboarding process,

00:10:18.870 --> 00:10:21.250
as illustrated by Joe
Ranft, our head of story.

00:10:21.250 --> 00:10:24.820
-Yes, so there's the
little, cute, Mr. Storyboard

00:10:24.820 --> 00:10:28.702
Artist working very diligently
and happily in January.

00:10:28.702 --> 00:10:29.660
-And he has a deadline.

00:10:29.660 --> 00:10:31.846
He's working hard
to do his sequence.

00:10:31.846 --> 00:10:34.220
Every time he does a drawing,
he pins it up on the board.

00:10:34.220 --> 00:10:36.803
And there, he stands back when
he gets done with his sequence.

00:10:36.803 --> 00:10:38.960
And he says, hmmm, did
I do it the best way?

00:10:38.960 --> 00:10:42.030
And storyboarding
actually balances, like,

00:10:42.030 --> 00:10:45.730
composition, cutting, staging,
acting, writing, everything

00:10:45.730 --> 00:10:49.470
that goes through the storyboard
artist's mind as he's doing it.

00:10:49.470 --> 00:10:52.970
-So he'll try another pass at
it a couple more times until he

00:10:52.970 --> 00:10:54.541
feels he's got it just right.

00:10:54.541 --> 00:10:55.040
-Just right.

00:10:55.040 --> 00:10:56.090
-It's perfect.

00:10:56.090 --> 00:10:58.040
-So he calls in the
story department--

00:10:58.040 --> 00:10:58.831
-And the directors.

00:10:58.831 --> 00:11:00.360
- --and, of course,
the director.

00:11:00.360 --> 00:11:01.580
-There you can
see John Lasseter.

00:11:01.580 --> 00:11:02.413
Looks just like him.

00:11:02.413 --> 00:11:05.140
-Yeah, it does, doesn't it?

00:11:05.140 --> 00:11:06.090
Thanks, Joe.

00:11:06.090 --> 00:11:09.110
-And then Joe-- or whoever's
pitching, the little storyboard

00:11:09.110 --> 00:11:11.405
artist, in this case--
will pitch the sequence.

00:11:11.405 --> 00:11:14.270
And in the middle of the
pitch, John gets an idea.

00:11:14.270 --> 00:11:15.287
-We all get ideas.

00:11:15.287 --> 00:11:17.745
And that's one of the great
things about storyboarding here

00:11:17.745 --> 00:11:21.140
at Pixar is it is a free-for-all
once we get in this.

00:11:21.140 --> 00:11:23.460
And everybody is out,
coming up with ideas

00:11:23.460 --> 00:11:26.190
to make the sequence better,
to make the film better.

00:11:26.190 --> 00:11:29.180
And when the pitch
session is done,

00:11:29.180 --> 00:11:31.600
inevitably there
is lots of ideas

00:11:31.600 --> 00:11:33.020
to make the sequence better.

00:11:33.020 --> 00:11:35.304
The storyboard artist
kind of wakes up from it.

00:11:35.304 --> 00:11:37.470
-Right, and we're infamous
for putting all our notes

00:11:37.470 --> 00:11:38.290
on little post-its.

00:11:38.290 --> 00:11:38.710
-Yeah.

00:11:38.710 --> 00:11:41.043
-That's why you see all the
little yellow squares there.

00:11:41.043 --> 00:11:42.970
And so we'll all leave,
all excited about

00:11:42.970 --> 00:11:45.120
the great new ideas we've got.

00:11:45.120 --> 00:11:46.604
And then the storyboard artist--

00:11:46.604 --> 00:11:48.770
-Mr. Storyboard Artist goes
back and thinks about it

00:11:48.770 --> 00:11:52.010
and starts over with all
his notes that he has to do.

00:11:52.010 --> 00:11:55.650
Joe Ranft often calls it--
the storyboarding process--

00:11:55.650 --> 00:11:57.680
not storyboarding,
but "story-reboarding"

00:11:57.680 --> 00:12:01.480
because we work on it,
redo it, redo it, redo it,

00:12:01.480 --> 00:12:04.860
to make each sequence, to make
the entire film as best as we

00:12:04.860 --> 00:12:06.256
possibly can be.

