AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:51:29.310 --> 00:51:31.999
JOHN: Maybe you use the heavy
machinery to move the rocks.

00:51:31.999 --> 00:51:33.790
And then we just move
our little character.

00:51:33.790 --> 00:51:37.060
And he can move the feathers.

00:51:37.060 --> 00:51:39.280
JOSH: Yeah, that could work.

00:51:39.280 --> 00:51:41.350
Like, a big backhoe
has to move the rocks.

00:51:41.350 --> 00:51:46.000
But the character
is able to just

00:51:46.000 --> 00:51:48.569
either blow on the
feathers or move them out

00:51:48.569 --> 00:51:49.610
of the way really easily.

00:51:59.410 --> 00:52:01.860
JOHN: Can you see
a little berm here?

00:52:01.860 --> 00:52:04.080
JOSH: OK, yeah, that's nice.

00:52:06.950 --> 00:52:07.835
That work?

00:52:07.835 --> 00:52:10.030
Does that "sell it," as we say?

00:52:17.250 --> 00:52:21.760
So we need to show
that the-- do we

00:52:21.760 --> 00:52:24.374
need to show the backhoe first?

00:52:24.374 --> 00:52:25.790
"It would take a
lot more effort--

00:52:25.790 --> 00:52:27.710
or force-- to move
the pile of rocks."

00:52:27.710 --> 00:52:30.270
And then we have another
shot-- "than it would

00:52:30.270 --> 00:52:44.240
to move the pile of feathers."

00:52:44.240 --> 00:52:47.452
We see the rocks gone
in the next scene.

00:52:47.452 --> 00:52:49.450
JOHN: Right here they're gone?

00:52:49.450 --> 00:52:49.950
JOSH: Yeah.

00:53:39.102 --> 00:53:41.018
So he gets through-- so
the feathers are gone.

00:53:54.000 --> 00:53:57.580
And then we've got
another line here.

00:53:57.580 --> 00:54:01.290
"The reason rocks have
more mass than feathers

00:54:01.290 --> 00:54:10.756
because they're more dense."

00:54:10.756 --> 00:54:14.364
AUDIENCE: Maybe you could,
like, have a scale with, like,

00:54:14.364 --> 00:54:15.676
the backhoe with rocks on it.

00:54:15.676 --> 00:54:19.120
And you've got feathers
on it or something.

00:54:19.120 --> 00:54:22.110
[INAUDIBLE]

00:54:22.110 --> 00:54:23.200
JOSH: Is it-- yeah.

00:54:23.200 --> 00:54:26.780
AUDIENCE: That's why I was,
like, it's not a type of scale.

00:54:26.780 --> 00:54:29.014
JOSH: Right, right.

00:54:29.014 --> 00:54:31.430
I'm not a scientist-- and you
guys can help me with this--

00:54:31.430 --> 00:54:36.720
but does density really
equate to weight?

00:54:36.720 --> 00:54:38.790
If we just show them on
a scale, does that really

00:54:38.790 --> 00:54:41.372
show that one is more
dense than the other?

00:54:41.372 --> 00:54:42.538
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I guess not.

00:54:46.400 --> 00:54:48.320
AUDIENCE: I mean, it's indirect.

00:54:48.320 --> 00:54:51.656
So maybe a better way
would be to address density

00:54:51.656 --> 00:54:52.930
more directly?

00:54:52.930 --> 00:54:53.430
JOSH: Yeah.

00:54:58.010 --> 00:55:02.840
Could we do something,
like-- just very simple,

00:55:02.840 --> 00:55:09.580
where we just-- the
character extends two hands.

00:55:09.580 --> 00:55:10.730
In one hand is a rock.

00:55:10.730 --> 00:55:12.600
And in the other is a feather.

00:55:12.600 --> 00:55:19.690
And we just-- and we
put the words more

00:55:19.690 --> 00:55:23.070
dense above the hand
with the rock in it

00:55:23.070 --> 00:55:26.030
or something like that?

00:55:26.030 --> 00:55:32.431
How do you visually say
something is more dense?

00:55:32.431 --> 00:55:33.930
Like, how do you
show that visually?

00:55:33.930 --> 00:55:35.346
AUDIENCE: The
tractor, or whatever

00:55:35.346 --> 00:55:39.010
that heavy machine was, it
could be throwing the rocks off

00:55:39.010 --> 00:55:39.731
into the ocean.

00:55:39.731 --> 00:55:41.204
And you see the rocks sinking.

00:55:41.204 --> 00:55:44.641
And then the feathers are just
floating in the air, maybe just

00:55:44.641 --> 00:55:46.605
landing on the surface.

00:55:46.605 --> 00:55:48.112
JOSH: That's an
interesting idea.

00:55:48.112 --> 00:55:49.570
AUDIENCE: It
definitely shows that.

00:55:49.570 --> 00:55:52.215
And I'm not sure how
familiar the kids will

00:55:52.215 --> 00:55:54.312
be with the concept of density.

00:55:57.010 --> 00:55:59.826
But having the water--
sinking, floating,

00:55:59.826 --> 00:56:02.814
maybe-- makes the
point a bit better.

00:56:05.330 --> 00:56:09.515
AUDIENCE: You already
introduced volume.

00:56:09.515 --> 00:56:11.506
So I feel like to
introduce density

00:56:11.506 --> 00:56:14.784
wouldn't really be
doing, like, what

00:56:14.784 --> 00:56:15.992
came before, which is volume.

00:56:15.992 --> 00:56:17.533
I don't think it
would do it justice.

00:56:17.533 --> 00:56:20.210
Because density is
volume and mass.

00:56:20.210 --> 00:56:24.790
So if you're able to have volume
and then go to mass after that,

00:56:24.790 --> 00:56:27.380
I think that's where
they'd connect,

00:56:27.380 --> 00:56:29.280
that the mass could
be different even

00:56:29.280 --> 00:56:31.280
though the volume is the same.

00:56:31.280 --> 00:56:35.232
And you would still have
different densities.

00:56:35.232 --> 00:56:36.660
ELIZABETH: I mean,
the other thing

00:56:36.660 --> 00:56:38.730
is that the video isn't
really about density.

00:56:38.730 --> 00:56:42.041
The video is about
mass and acceleration.

00:56:42.041 --> 00:56:42.540
JOSH: Yeah.

00:56:42.540 --> 00:56:44.436
ELIZABETH: So it
may not even be--

00:56:44.436 --> 00:56:46.665
and, like, this is sacrilege--
but it may not even

00:56:46.665 --> 00:56:48.610
be that important
to really define

00:56:48.610 --> 00:56:50.970
what density is in this
particular video, which

00:56:50.970 --> 00:56:54.240
is why maybe it's
OK to say one's more

00:56:54.240 --> 00:56:55.700
dense than the other.

00:56:55.700 --> 00:56:58.060
It's like, a couple
minute video?

00:56:58.060 --> 00:56:59.791
JOSH: Yeah.

00:56:59.791 --> 00:57:01.290
ELIZABETH: The point
is really about

00:57:01.290 --> 00:57:05.220
how things that have more
mass require more force.

00:57:05.220 --> 00:57:06.960
If you start going
into density, I'm

00:57:06.960 --> 00:57:09.240
afraid that people
would also want

00:57:09.240 --> 00:57:12.850
to talk about what the
difference between weight

00:57:12.850 --> 00:57:13.820
and mass are, too.

00:57:13.820 --> 00:57:15.610
JOSH: Yeah, true.

00:57:15.610 --> 00:57:17.960
ELIZABETH: So again, it's
like, at what point are you

00:57:17.960 --> 00:57:20.633
branching off too much
from the point of the video

00:57:20.633 --> 00:57:22.600
and the main point of the story?

00:57:22.600 --> 00:57:24.100
JOSH: That's a good point, yeah.

00:57:29.200 --> 00:57:33.470
Well, "The reason rocks
have more mass than feathers

00:57:33.470 --> 00:57:36.480
because they're more dense."

00:57:36.480 --> 00:57:40.300
Yeah, so maybe--
I don't remember

00:57:40.300 --> 00:57:42.965
what we did in the video we
actually ended up producing.

00:57:48.310 --> 00:57:52.800
I think I would go with the
hand displaying the two things

00:57:52.800 --> 00:57:56.560
and think about how they're
essentially the same size.

00:57:56.560 --> 00:58:01.730
But one is very light
and one is this rock.

00:58:01.730 --> 00:58:02.745
It's dense.

00:58:02.745 --> 00:58:07.180
ELIZABETH: Can you-- is
it possible to zoom in

00:58:07.180 --> 00:58:08.430
on the rock?

00:58:08.430 --> 00:58:11.675
Because density is really that
there's more stuff per space,

00:58:11.675 --> 00:58:12.990
right?

00:58:12.990 --> 00:58:15.810
So somehow have the
rock bulge a little bit

00:58:15.810 --> 00:58:18.130
to show that frame
is like stuffed

00:58:18.130 --> 00:58:19.890
with as much stuff as possible.

00:58:19.890 --> 00:58:20.390
JOSH: Yeah.

00:58:20.390 --> 00:58:24.176
ELIZABETH: And then
show the feathers

00:58:24.176 --> 00:58:28.370
and show like a lot more air and
space in between the feathers.

00:58:28.370 --> 00:58:30.460
And you can still put
the label "more dense."

00:58:30.460 --> 00:58:33.200
But maybe there'd be some
sort of visual cue associated

00:58:33.200 --> 00:58:34.345
with that as well.

00:58:34.345 --> 00:58:35.345
JOSH: Yeah, potentially.

00:58:39.840 --> 00:58:42.025
This is a toughie.

00:58:42.025 --> 00:58:44.150
JOHN: So you're saying,
maybe, we cut to a new shot

00:58:44.150 --> 00:58:47.440
where we see a rock and
a feather side by side?

00:58:47.440 --> 00:58:50.000
And then maybe we
see like, a view

00:58:50.000 --> 00:58:52.279
of each one under a microscope?

00:58:52.279 --> 00:58:53.820
ELIZABETH: Almost,
but again, I don't

00:58:53.820 --> 00:58:56.285
know if that's distracting
too much from the main point

00:58:56.285 --> 00:58:59.450
of the story.

00:58:59.450 --> 00:59:03.060
JOSH: Well, I like that
idea-- the microscope image.

00:59:03.060 --> 00:59:05.450
Like, we show like the
crystalline structure

00:59:05.450 --> 00:59:10.501
of the rock is really, it's like
a lot of stuff packed in there.

00:59:10.501 --> 00:59:11.974
AUDIENCE: What if he was poking?

00:59:11.974 --> 00:59:16.393
So you can't poke a rock but
maybe he takes out a pencil

00:59:16.393 --> 00:59:18.848
and pokes through the feather.

00:59:18.848 --> 00:59:20.321
We can do that [INAUDIBLE]

00:59:23.267 --> 00:59:25.722
AUDIENCE: I think
it's too complicated

00:59:25.722 --> 00:59:29.190
to go with this concept.

00:59:29.190 --> 00:59:31.111
Like, I don't know.

00:59:31.111 --> 00:59:36.675
The word "dense," like, I
don't think we have to-- I

00:59:36.675 --> 00:59:39.460
don't know if we have to
explain that right now.

00:59:39.460 --> 00:59:43.000
JOSH: Yeah, well, let's think
of another strategy here.

00:59:43.000 --> 00:59:46.710
How necessary do you think
this line is in the script?

00:59:46.710 --> 00:59:50.000
I mean, is it vital to
the script itself, I mean,

00:59:50.000 --> 00:59:51.733
to the whole story?

00:59:51.733 --> 00:59:53.300
I don't know, I
haven't given you

00:59:53.300 --> 00:59:55.080
guys a chance to
read the whole thing.

00:59:55.080 --> 00:59:57.770
But maybe this is
one of those moments

00:59:57.770 --> 00:59:59.280
where we take this line out.

00:59:59.280 --> 01:00:04.500
And we end the paragraph
with moving the feathers.

01:00:04.500 --> 01:00:06.220
AUDIENCE: Well, it's far easier.

01:00:06.220 --> 01:00:08.160
JOSH: Yeah, it is easier.

01:00:08.160 --> 01:00:10.470
And it might be one
of those moments

01:00:10.470 --> 01:00:15.532
where this line is a distraction
from the-- I think that's where

01:00:15.532 --> 01:00:16.990
we're struggling right now.

01:00:16.990 --> 01:00:18.620
JOSH: Yeah, yeah.

01:00:18.620 --> 01:00:22.380
So let's say, OK, we're going
to remove this line for now.

01:00:22.380 --> 01:00:27.600
And some client is
gonna come to you

01:00:27.600 --> 01:00:29.750
and say, well, why did you
guys take that line out?

01:00:29.750 --> 01:00:30.900
We really need that.

01:00:30.900 --> 01:00:33.200
And then you have
to argue for that.

01:00:33.200 --> 01:00:35.310
That's all part of
the process, right?

01:00:35.310 --> 01:00:38.650
Like, well, we talked about
this for about an hour.

01:00:38.650 --> 01:00:41.220
And we realized that
this wasn't really

01:00:41.220 --> 01:00:42.687
important to the process.

01:00:42.687 --> 01:00:43.520
You know, and that--

01:00:43.520 --> 01:00:45.186
AUDIENCE: How often
do you feel like you

01:00:45.186 --> 01:00:47.400
have to, like, you have
an artistic vision of what

01:00:47.400 --> 01:00:49.221
direction it should go?

01:00:49.221 --> 01:00:50.470
JOSH: It happens all the time.

01:00:50.470 --> 01:00:50.840
Yeah,

01:00:50.840 --> 01:00:52.000
AUDIENCE: And then
you have to comment?

01:00:52.000 --> 01:00:53.580
JOSH: In my
professional opinion--

01:00:53.580 --> 01:00:55.430
and that's when I
have to sort of fake

01:00:55.430 --> 01:01:01.820
this professional persona--
we don't think you

01:01:01.820 --> 01:01:04.100
should have this
line in the script.

01:01:04.100 --> 01:01:07.980
And in retrospect, this
line is in the video we--

01:01:07.980 --> 01:01:10.530
but we didn't have 15 people
to talk about it with.

01:01:10.530 --> 01:01:12.690
We only had four.

01:01:12.690 --> 01:01:16.140
ELIZABETH: But do you see how--
like, are people OK with taking

01:01:16.140 --> 01:01:17.280
that line out now?

01:01:17.280 --> 01:01:19.546
Like, you see why maybe
that's a good choice?

01:01:19.546 --> 01:01:22.180
Would you have reacted
that positively

01:01:22.180 --> 01:01:25.945
to the idea of taking this out
maybe five days ago, before we

01:01:25.945 --> 01:01:27.315
had gone through this class?

01:01:27.315 --> 01:01:28.822
Because I feel that
is the reaction

01:01:28.822 --> 01:01:29.780
of a lot of scientists.

01:01:29.780 --> 01:01:31.529
Like, wait, wait,
wait-- this is accurate,

01:01:31.529 --> 01:01:34.120
but it's not precise, like
you were just talking about.

01:01:34.120 --> 01:01:36.120
You have to talk about density.

01:01:36.120 --> 01:01:37.760
And that's sort
of-- I mean, I want

01:01:37.760 --> 01:01:40.760
to tie this back to the work
that you guys are doing now.

01:01:40.760 --> 01:01:42.855
You guys see how this
process is really

01:01:42.855 --> 01:01:47.060
making you examine
what is truly necessary

01:01:47.060 --> 01:01:48.780
and what isn't to the project.

01:01:48.780 --> 01:01:51.150
Because this is going to
happen to your scripts, too.

01:01:51.150 --> 01:01:52.691
You're gonna sit
down and storyboard.

01:01:52.691 --> 01:01:55.080
And you're gonna rack your
brain over one sentence

01:01:55.080 --> 01:01:57.460
that you can't think of
an appropriate visual for.

01:01:57.460 --> 01:02:00.180
And maybe that's a key for you
to reconsider whether or not

01:02:00.180 --> 01:02:02.530
that part is truly vital.

01:02:02.530 --> 01:02:05.060
But you are not forced to
do that until you think

01:02:05.060 --> 01:02:06.960
about things like
storyboarding and think

01:02:06.960 --> 01:02:10.380
about things like an overall
narrative to your video.

01:02:10.380 --> 01:02:13.980
Because otherwise you're going
to do what most scientists do.

01:02:13.980 --> 01:02:18.886
And I-- I mean, I say this
as a former amateur would.

01:02:18.886 --> 01:02:22.150
But the tendency is to just
throw as much information

01:02:22.150 --> 01:02:24.860
out there to cover
your grounds, right?

01:02:24.860 --> 01:02:26.770
JOSH: Yeah, and I
think-- if I remember

01:02:26.770 --> 01:02:30.960
correctly-- this script
was a lot more complicated.

01:02:30.960 --> 01:02:33.990
We received a kind of rough
script from the client.

01:02:33.990 --> 01:02:37.680
And I had to edit it down
and get it into something

01:02:37.680 --> 01:02:40.310
that worked for the medium.

01:02:43.950 --> 01:02:46.260
And we had some
discussions about well,

01:02:46.260 --> 01:02:47.870
like, why can't we say that?

01:02:47.870 --> 01:02:51.490
I mean, exactly what you're
talking about happened.

01:02:51.490 --> 01:02:54.205
And I think that this one
just sort of slipped through.

01:02:54.205 --> 01:02:55.080
This one got through.

01:02:55.080 --> 01:02:56.890
And, in retrospect,
maybe we shouldn't

01:02:56.890 --> 01:03:00.280
have produced that line.

01:03:00.280 --> 01:03:03.040
But I love that we're
thinking about this.

01:03:03.040 --> 01:03:06.090
I think this is a really cool--
this is a really important part

01:03:06.090 --> 01:03:07.100
of the process.

01:03:07.100 --> 01:03:08.975
AUDIENCE: This goes back
to the core concept.

01:03:08.975 --> 01:03:11.480
I mean, the core, number one
thing is know your audience.

01:03:11.480 --> 01:03:13.940
Think about your audience.

01:03:13.940 --> 01:03:15.710
I was actually
earlier today helping

01:03:15.710 --> 01:03:18.590
one of my graduate fellows
apply for the master's

01:03:18.590 --> 01:03:21.600
in journalism program here.

01:03:21.600 --> 01:03:25.748
And she has to write a 500-word
piece on a science topic.

01:03:25.748 --> 01:03:30.510
And she was trying her hardest
to consolidate an experiment.

01:03:30.510 --> 01:03:32.440
And she was trying
to think about what

01:03:32.440 --> 01:03:34.600
the lay audience cares about.

01:03:34.600 --> 01:03:36.445
And it was so hard for her.

01:03:36.445 --> 01:03:39.965
And she distilled it down
to two and a half sentences.

01:03:39.965 --> 01:03:44.080
But I told her even that was
too much for a New York Times

01:03:44.080 --> 01:03:47.550
piece, that no one cares about
which mice were chosen and why

01:03:47.550 --> 01:03:48.495
for this experiment.

01:03:48.495 --> 01:03:52.912
And then-- that this is the
crux of, like, what I think

01:03:52.912 --> 01:03:54.220
is one of the hardest things.

01:03:54.220 --> 01:03:54.740
JOSH: Right.

01:03:54.740 --> 01:03:57.640
And there was-- I think on
Monday we heard this phrase,

01:03:57.640 --> 01:03:59.120
"kill your darlings."

01:03:59.120 --> 01:04:00.260
There's that--

01:04:00.260 --> 01:04:02.550
AUDIENCE: And that'll
come back [INAUDIBLE].

01:04:02.550 --> 01:04:03.930
It's my favorite.

01:04:03.930 --> 01:04:08.890
JOSH: Yeah, exactly.

01:04:08.890 --> 01:04:11.510
And I think, in
retrospect, introducing

01:04:11.510 --> 01:04:15.450
the notion of density into
this is a real distraction.

01:04:15.450 --> 01:04:17.520
It's not what this is about.

01:04:17.520 --> 01:04:20.220
So yeah, I would
say let's strike

01:04:20.220 --> 01:04:24.670
that line-- that we have
the luxury of doing that.

01:04:24.670 --> 01:04:29.370
So I want to stop there
with our portion of it.

01:04:29.370 --> 01:04:32.520
And then kind of let you
guys break up into groups

01:04:32.520 --> 01:04:35.750
and do maybe the
next two paragraphs.

01:04:35.750 --> 01:04:37.300
If you make it
further, that's fine.

01:04:39.870 --> 01:04:43.530
And then we'll walk around
and to you about your ideas.

01:04:43.530 --> 01:04:46.020
But-- so how many
of us are there?

01:04:46.020 --> 01:04:47.140
1-2-- there's seven?

01:04:47.140 --> 01:04:48.830
ELIZABETH: There are eight.

01:04:48.830 --> 01:04:49.380
JOSH: Eight?

01:04:49.380 --> 01:04:52.255
OK, so that is nice--
two groups of four.

01:04:56.284 --> 01:04:58.200
Yeah, I'll let you divide
up however you want.

01:04:58.200 --> 01:05:00.658
If you just want to go with
you four over here and then you

01:05:00.658 --> 01:05:01.920
four over here is fine.

01:05:04.450 --> 01:05:10.820
You guys from this-- are you
guys, I would say not all three

01:05:10.820 --> 01:05:13.820
of you guys together because you
know each other and all that.

01:05:16.530 --> 01:05:18.720
But yeah, that's let's
get started with that.

01:05:18.720 --> 01:05:20.326
ELIZABETH: And if you guys
need to take a break to go

01:05:20.326 --> 01:05:22.551
to the bathroom, this is a
wonderful opportunity to do

01:05:22.551 --> 01:05:23.150
that since we're--

01:05:23.150 --> 01:05:24.191
JOSH: That's a good idea.

01:05:24.191 --> 01:05:24.740
Yeah, yeah.

01:05:24.740 --> 01:05:26.510
