01:12:59.610 --> 01:13:01.490
-Mass a measure of
an object's ability

01:13:01.490 --> 01:13:04.350
to resist being
accelerated by a force.

01:13:04.350 --> 01:13:06.930
That means the more
massive an object is,

01:13:06.930 --> 01:13:10.470
the harder it is to make
it move if it's at rest

01:13:10.470 --> 01:13:13.580
or to stop it if it's moving.

01:13:13.580 --> 01:13:16.650
The nifty thing about mass
is that doesn't necessarily

01:13:16.650 --> 01:13:18.840
have to do with size.

01:13:18.840 --> 01:13:22.770
Think of a big pile of rocks
and a big pile of feathers.

01:13:22.770 --> 01:13:25.550
Both piles are the
same size, or volume.

01:13:25.550 --> 01:13:27.330
But it would take
a lot more effort--

01:13:27.330 --> 01:13:29.720
or force-- to move
the pile of rocks

01:13:29.720 --> 01:13:32.170
than it would to move
the pile of feathers.

01:13:32.170 --> 01:13:33.150
The reason?

01:13:33.150 --> 01:13:35.160
Rocks have more
mass than feathers

01:13:35.160 --> 01:13:37.120
because they're more dense.

01:13:37.120 --> 01:13:39.220
To show how it's harder
to accelerate something

01:13:39.220 --> 01:13:42.940
with more mass, picture a
student and a teacher each

01:13:42.940 --> 01:13:46.410
sitting at rest in a rolling
chair facing each other.

01:13:46.410 --> 01:13:50.100
Let's also say the teacher is
more massive than the student.

01:13:50.100 --> 01:13:51.650
When they both push
off each other,

01:13:51.650 --> 01:13:53.800
they go rolling backwards.

01:13:53.800 --> 01:13:56.670
Notice how the student
goes back much farther

01:13:56.670 --> 01:13:59.130
and faster than the teacher.

01:13:59.130 --> 01:14:02.800
The teacher accelerates less,
since she is the more massive

01:14:02.800 --> 01:14:04.190
of the two objects.

01:14:04.190 --> 01:14:06.740
And it takes more
force to accelerate her

01:14:06.740 --> 01:14:08.510
than it does the student.

01:14:08.510 --> 01:14:11.580
All of this has to do with
Newton's Second Law of Motion--

01:14:11.580 --> 01:14:13.600
f equals ma.

01:14:13.600 --> 01:14:17.780
It says, for a set acceleration,
an object with more mass

01:14:17.780 --> 01:14:20.400
requires more force
to get it moving

01:14:20.400 --> 01:14:22.680
at that set acceleration.

01:14:22.680 --> 01:14:25.160
As mass increases,
the force required

01:14:25.160 --> 01:14:30.930
to accelerate or decelerate
that mass increases as well.

01:14:30.930 --> 01:14:33.070
Now don't you feel
massively smarter?

