01:20:57.196 --> 01:20:58.678
AUDIENCE: How much is one scene?

01:20:58.678 --> 01:21:00.160
So what does that entail?

01:21:03.470 --> 01:21:08.780
ELIZABETH: Well, I think of
scenes as sort of locations

01:21:08.780 --> 01:21:09.900
almost.

01:21:09.900 --> 01:21:28.600
And so let me go back to--
sorry, my lap-- bye, Jamie.

01:21:33.979 --> 01:21:39.950
A scene kind of encompasses
a general statement.

01:21:39.950 --> 01:21:44.120
So that the way I
broke up the storyboard

01:21:44.120 --> 01:21:47.810
is I basically just did
stills of each scene.

01:21:47.810 --> 01:21:50.270
You can kind of consider
the whole top row

01:21:50.270 --> 01:21:52.260
as, like, a general
scene, one which is

01:21:52.260 --> 01:21:53.610
how I originally scripted it.

01:21:53.610 --> 01:21:56.090
It was just sort of like
the visual introduction

01:21:56.090 --> 01:22:00.430
to the video.

01:22:00.430 --> 01:22:02.380
But breaking it up
into scenes is nice,

01:22:02.380 --> 01:22:05.930
because then you'll notice if
one scene has a lot of text.

01:22:05.930 --> 01:22:08.980
And then you have a scene right
afterwards that's very short.

01:22:08.980 --> 01:22:11.550
And you just have a series
of really quick scenes.

01:22:11.550 --> 01:22:14.540
Maybe you can think about
restructuring or spreading

01:22:14.540 --> 01:22:17.280
out the material
a little bit more.

01:22:17.280 --> 01:22:19.120
Because, like I said,
what you don't want

01:22:19.120 --> 01:22:23.970
is either really long
shots or really long scenes

01:22:23.970 --> 01:22:25.770
where you're not really
changing that much,

01:22:25.770 --> 01:22:30.090
or if you're doing too
many, really quick changes.

01:22:30.090 --> 01:22:31.040
But I don't know.

01:22:31.040 --> 01:22:34.401
I don't have a good definition
for what a scene technically

01:22:34.401 --> 01:22:34.900
is.

01:22:36.985 --> 01:22:38.693
JOSH: It's kind of a
unit of information.

01:22:41.328 --> 01:22:44.316
When I think about writing,
I think about paragraphs.

01:22:44.316 --> 01:22:47.802
This is kind of a
discrete unit that's

01:22:47.802 --> 01:22:50.590
imparting a certain
part of the narrative.

01:22:50.590 --> 01:22:53.540
And that's-- for
me, that's a scene.

01:22:53.540 --> 01:22:55.920
ELIZABETH: Yeah.

01:22:55.920 --> 01:22:59.440
I think the way I'd scripted
it, those four shots

01:22:59.440 --> 01:23:00.660
are all different locations.

01:23:00.660 --> 01:23:03.870
But I listed it as scene one.

01:23:03.870 --> 01:23:06.460
Like, where you see
Professor Ribbeck

01:23:06.460 --> 01:23:08.940
and then I'm right
there in front of her,

01:23:08.940 --> 01:23:11.000
I also chunk that
together as one scene.

01:23:11.000 --> 01:23:12.880
But then, when we
were editing and sort

01:23:12.880 --> 01:23:16.010
of taking note of
all the clips, we

01:23:16.010 --> 01:23:19.080
denoted one as like scene
five and then the one

01:23:19.080 --> 01:23:22.410
after as scene five
A. But, in general,

01:23:22.410 --> 01:23:23.760
like it's the same sort of idea.

01:23:23.760 --> 01:23:25.834
We're in her lab
in that portion.

01:23:28.696 --> 01:23:30.510
Does anyone have
any other questions?

01:23:30.510 --> 01:23:33.498
AUDIENCE: What was, like, the
motivation in using professor

01:23:33.498 --> 01:23:35.220
to--

01:23:35.220 --> 01:23:36.880
ELIZABETH: So, in
this particular one,

01:23:36.880 --> 01:23:39.210
I wanted to highlight
the research that

01:23:39.210 --> 01:23:40.930
was going on here.

01:23:40.930 --> 01:23:44.890
And I also wanted to get her
involved because I knew her.

01:23:44.890 --> 01:23:47.880
And I really like her.

01:23:47.880 --> 01:23:50.560
And it was sort of
like a quirky breaking

01:23:50.560 --> 01:23:51.780
down the fourth wall moment.

01:23:51.780 --> 01:23:54.690
So what happens
in this scene is--

01:23:54.690 --> 01:23:57.390
I set it up in the previous
scene as saying snot

01:23:57.390 --> 01:23:58.930
is more than just this.

01:23:58.930 --> 01:24:00.090
And then it jumps to her.

01:24:00.090 --> 01:24:01.380
And she finishes my sentence.

01:24:01.380 --> 01:24:04.160
And she goes, it's actually xyz.

01:24:04.160 --> 01:24:05.670
And then it cuts
to a wider shot,

01:24:05.670 --> 01:24:08.450
revealing that I'm in
front of her, interviewing.

01:24:08.450 --> 01:24:10.420
And you see the camera
interviewing her.

01:24:10.420 --> 01:24:10.740
And I'm, like--

01:24:10.740 --> 01:24:11.160
[GESTURING TOWARDS PROFESSOR]

01:24:11.160 --> 01:24:12.409
And then I go, she would know.

01:24:12.409 --> 01:24:14.600
And then her name
sort of pops up.

01:24:14.600 --> 01:24:17.420
Partially because we wanted
to have her in the video,

01:24:17.420 --> 01:24:20.410
but we didn't want it
to be really formal.

01:24:20.410 --> 01:24:23.449
Because that shot is a very
traditional formal interview.

01:24:23.449 --> 01:24:24.740
So we wanted to make it quirky.

01:24:24.740 --> 01:24:27.610
And we also wanted to sort
of like informalize it.

01:24:27.610 --> 01:24:30.500
So that's why we
broke out of that.

01:24:30.500 --> 01:24:32.630
And I did the whole
like, she would now.

01:24:32.630 --> 01:24:36.234
And then we could make that
setup a little more fun.

01:24:36.234 --> 01:24:41.211
AUDIENCE: How do you think
about the authority of the host,

01:24:41.211 --> 01:24:41.710
right?

01:24:41.710 --> 01:24:45.162
Because you can say things
that are easily verifiable.

01:24:45.162 --> 01:24:46.870
But then if you're
going to say something

01:24:46.870 --> 01:24:50.310
about snot that, like, most
people don't know, then

01:24:50.310 --> 01:24:52.820
on whose authority
do you say this?

01:24:52.820 --> 01:24:54.780
I've watched like an
Alton Brown thing.

01:24:54.780 --> 01:24:57.720
And I was like, all
right, that's wrong.

01:24:57.720 --> 01:24:59.840
And like, but you are
talking about all the things

01:24:59.840 --> 01:25:00.860
I want to know.

01:25:00.860 --> 01:25:02.880
And now I don't know
when you're lying to me.

01:25:02.880 --> 01:25:05.175
ELIZABETH: Yeah, well,
I mean, part of it is,

01:25:05.175 --> 01:25:08.130
that's the responsibility
that you have as the host,

01:25:08.130 --> 01:25:10.150
is that the viewer
has, by default,

01:25:10.150 --> 01:25:11.760
placed their trust in you.

01:25:11.760 --> 01:25:14.610
I think with us, we're
not going to have as much

01:25:14.610 --> 01:25:17.100
of a problem to prove because
everyone knows that all

01:25:17.100 --> 01:25:19.090
the hosts are students at MIT.

01:25:19.090 --> 01:25:20.820
And in our YouTube
descriptions, we

01:25:20.820 --> 01:25:22.960
say that all the scripts
were fact-checked

01:25:22.960 --> 01:25:25.930
by postdoc researchers.

01:25:25.930 --> 01:25:28.160
For this, I mean, that
was one of the reasons

01:25:28.160 --> 01:25:31.250
why we used her is because I
could explain her research.

01:25:31.250 --> 01:25:34.100
Or I could just have
her say it, which

01:25:34.100 --> 01:25:36.760
I thought was like a cooler
window into the world

01:25:36.760 --> 01:25:39.120
here, which is what I was
talking on the first day.

01:25:39.120 --> 01:25:40.911
How do you create the
window into the world

01:25:40.911 --> 01:25:43.830
that people don't
have access to?

01:25:43.830 --> 01:25:46.570
I also studied bioengineering
for my undergrad.

01:25:46.570 --> 01:25:48.700
So all the material
for the script

01:25:48.700 --> 01:25:52.860
came from the class I took
from Professor Ribbeck.

01:25:52.860 --> 01:25:58.480
But I think you don't take the
time in your video to introduce

01:25:58.480 --> 01:25:59.820
yourself necessarily.

01:25:59.820 --> 01:26:01.180
And maybe you should.

01:26:01.180 --> 01:26:03.217
That's always something
we've considered,

01:26:03.217 --> 01:26:05.550
is that something that we
need to introduce into Science

01:26:05.550 --> 01:26:06.500
Out Loud.

01:26:06.500 --> 01:26:08.990
The host saying at the
beginning, like, I'm Jack

01:26:08.990 --> 01:26:14.642
and I work at MIT's D-lab.

01:26:14.642 --> 01:26:16.850
And that's sort of what we
did with Lindsey's episode

01:26:16.850 --> 01:26:19.240
just a tiny bit.

01:26:19.240 --> 01:26:22.820
But there are ways of
establishing authority

01:26:22.820 --> 01:26:24.580
where you don't have
to vocally do it.

01:26:24.580 --> 01:26:28.290
So in Lindsey's episode,
we filmed at MIT is D-lab.

01:26:28.290 --> 01:26:31.510
And instead of saying,
like, we're at MIT's D-lab,

01:26:31.510 --> 01:26:35.600
we just spent a few seconds
doing shots of the sign that

01:26:35.600 --> 01:26:37.650
said D-lab, basically.

01:26:37.650 --> 01:26:42.084
If you guys want to see
it, I can show you later.

01:26:42.084 --> 01:26:43.750
But I don't have a
good answer for that,

01:26:43.750 --> 01:26:46.640
because I think that, even
if you're Stephen Hawking,

01:26:46.640 --> 01:26:49.560
people can question
your authority to say

01:26:49.560 --> 01:26:50.610
the things you're saying.

01:26:50.610 --> 01:26:53.210
And the point of the
video isn't necessarily

01:26:53.210 --> 01:26:57.060
to establish that-- or at least
the point of these videos.

01:26:59.760 --> 01:27:02.484
Your material should
be accurate, though.

